photo.title: Ms. bio-bibliographical notes in Latin and Italian
photo.description: Boninus Mombritius Mediolanensis, hoc eodem tempore 1460 sub typographia [...] initium floruisse crediter .... multo annos in colligendis sanctorum Aelis[?] post anum [sic] 1460. inscripsisse videtur, quo typographia in usum litteratorum [...]it, ut ingentia duo volumina orbi oss[...] Inscribuntur Vit[a]e et Acta Sanctorum collecta et edita per Boninum Mombritium Mediolanensem. Vetus editio duobus volum. fol. Cum autem ubique nota temporis et loci h[a]ec impressa sint, hinc su[...]tes typo- graphi[a]e initium Mediolani vel alibi prodi[...] inter annum 1470 et 1480 visi harum rerum erudite con- jiciunt. De hac collectione insigni mentionem honorificari facit Joannes Bollandus Societatis Jesu in prefatione generali ad vitas sanctorum cap. 1. pag. 5. pag. [...] hisce [...]bis Boninus Mombritius Medio- "lanensis duo ingentia volumina edidit, quibis acta sanctorum completus est ut ea in MSS. codicibus se- "perit ita fideliter, ut ne [...]da quidam scriptiones correxerit, qu[a]e minus jucundam lectionem red- "dere solent. Dicavit illlud [...] quo sanctissimum inscripsit honestissimo Equite Cicho Simonet[a]e [...] "Mediolanensium secretario. H[a]ec Bollandus. Multa quoque alia opuscula composuisse legitur qu[a]e adhuc MSS. in bibliothecis extant. In Philippi Labbei Bibliotheca MSS. librorum hoc specimine an- tiquarum lectionem Gr[a]ecorum. Parisiis in 4o an. 1653 apud Joannem Henault ex MSS. codicibus Regi[a]e Galliarum Bibliothec[a]e potissimum collecta, ibidem in supplemento VIII quo [blank space] qu[a]edam ex catalogo MSS. codicum, qui continentur in 2a parte h[...] [blank space] bibliothec[a]e Regi[a]e, et in fascicules li brorum nondum compactis pag. 3 [blank space] Codice DCLXIX Bonini Mombritie de Varietate Fortun[a]e ad Galeatium Sfortiam Mediolani Ducum Ibidem pag. 305. Codice MLVIII Bonini Mombritie Poe- ma de nuptiis Tristian Vicecomitis. H[a]ec de MSS. nondum editis reciso[?] licuit latuitibus in Regia Galliarum Bibliotheca. Vixit autem usque ad annum 1496 Mombritius, quo edendum procusavit[?] Glossasicem[?] Papi[a]e Gramaticum, quod prefectum Venetiis in fol. anno dicto MCCCCXCVI die 19 men- sis aprilis. cujus ni fidem facit Carolus du Fresne Dominus du Conge ad Gloss[...]icem Medi[a]e et Jutim[a]e Latinitatis paragr. 44 pag. 36 Oudinus de scriptoribus Euleisi[a]e antiquis Tom. 3o pag. 265q. collegit ex quatuor Evangelistis hexametro casncine[?] Dominic[a]e Passionis ad Sixtum IV. S.M. libros sex, quorum initium est. Qui nineis[?] absunpsi primos juveniliter annos Michael a S. Josepho in Bibliographia Critica titulo Boninus [...] [...] Orlandi nel suo trattati dell' origine e progresso della stampa crede[?] il Mombrizio stampato in Milano i anno 1476. in circa nella Stamperia del Zaroni. photo.title: Armorial bookplate of George Dawson Coleman (1825-1878), American ironmaster, politician and philanthropist
photo.description: Armorial bookplate of George Dawson Coleman (1825-1878), American ironmaster, politician and philanthropist. Grandson of Robert Coleman, Pennsylvania's first millionaire, he studied at Princeton and received his A.M. from Penn in 1843. With his brother, Robert Coleman, he ran the family iron business (cf. Cornwall Iron Furnace) until Robert's retirement in 1857, after which he continued in sole charge until his death. In 1852 he married Deborah Brown (a scion of the Norris family through her mother) and had 13 children, 6 of whom survived to adulthood. Coleman served in the Pennsylvania General Assembly and Senate and was a founding member of the Pennsylvania State Board of Charities. Cf. his entry in J.W. Jordan, Encyclopedia of Pennsylvania Biography, v. 1 (New York: Lewis Historical Pub. Co., 1914). Penn Libraries call number: Inc M-499 Folio All images from this book

photo.title: Ms. ownership inscription of Gilbert Richard Redgrave (1844-1941)
photo.description: Ex libris. Gilbert R. Redgrave The Elms Beckenham, Kent. Feb. 1895 Note This is a fine copy of the first illustrated edition of Euclid, and it is probably the most magnificent work of the series produced by E. Ratdolt during his stay at Venice, from 1476 to 1486. It is No 26 of my "Bibliography" of this period of Ratdolt's activity. The leatherwork of the cover was designed and executed by me, and the binding is by Lachnsdorf. G.R.R. [Dated late 19th-century ms. ownership inscription and bibliographical note of Gilbert Richard Redgrave (1844-1941), English architect, art historian and bibliographer. With Alfred W. Pollard he coedited the STC, a standard reference work for books printed in the United Kingdom or in English elsewhere between 1475 and 1640. Lachnsdorf is probably Joseph Lachnsdorf, mentioned for his binding work here and here. Established heading: Redgrave, G. R. photo.title: Partially illegible blind stamp of Pancracio (sometimes Pancrazio) Lafita, a priest in Barbastro, Spain
photo.description: [...] Pancracio Lafita BARBASTRO [Partially illegible blind stamp of Pancracio (sometimes Pancrazio) Lafita, a priest in Barbastro, Spain. These documents identify him as "benefiziado-penitenziario de la Santa Iglesia Catedral de Barbastro" [curate-penitentiary of the Catedral de Santa María de la Asunción de Barbastro], as well as having some kind of supervisory authority over the parish of San Hipólito in 1891. By the turn of the twentieth century he was teaching at the seminary in Barbastro, where he appears to have been responsible for discovering the ms. of Ordinaciones y Paramientos de la Ciudad de Barbastro, a record of Barbastro's late 14th- and mid-15th century ordinances, subsequently edited and published by the historian Mariano de Pano y Ruata in 1905. He appears to have been a man of literary interests: from 1857-1873 he edited the periodical La Exposición de Sobarbe (cf. J.J. photo.title: Bookplate of Edward Heron-Allen (1861-1943)
photo.description: Bookplate of Edward Heron-Allen (1861-1943) Established heading: Heron-Allen, Edward, 1861-1943 The bookplate of Edward Heron-Allen (17 December 1861 – 28 March 1943), a writer, scientist, and Persian scholar, who produced a literal translation of the Quatrians of Omar Khayyam from the earliest known manuscript, which was in the Bodelian Library of Oxford University [1]. Another biographical sketch of him can be found on website maintained by the Heron-Allen Society [2]. The design elements of the bookplate illustrate a number of his interests. He was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society in May 1919 for his work in studying the Foraminifera, a class of microscopic amoeboid protists that produce their own shells, sometime with multiple chambers. Hence, the owl (symbol of learning), the microscope, and flanking his name, two examples of Foraminifera (compare to the samples in this photograph). He was an expert in the art of palmistry, and wrote several books on the subject, hence the palms at 9 and 3 o'clock of the circular device. As a young man, he learned the art of violin-making, and wrote a book on that topic, as well, hence the violin in the foreground. He was a scholar of Persian and translated the works of Omar Khayyam, and so Persian written in Arabic script appears in the bookplate, as well. He is also known as the author (under the pseudonym of Christopher Blayre) of The Cheetah Girl, a book that was suppressed because it dealt with themes of unconventional sexuality. Perhaps that is why a naked woman is being contemplated by the man in Persian garb. Given the fact that he wrote numerous books, he is found in VIAF.
